{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526007"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:19:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:19:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14108"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14108"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.12,0.08,0.67,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6787"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52757"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6787"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14108"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38132"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"251"},{"type":"tags","id":"517"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15032"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15034"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52757"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man presents with a nine-month history of upper abdominal pain and more recently vomiting and only being able to tolerate liquids. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He has a 15 pack-year smoking history and drinks two cans of beer daily. On examination, he appears unwell with vital signs within normal limits. His abdomen is soft but tender in the epigastrium. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Images 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following physical signs is most likely to be evident on examination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Shifting dullness","Palpable cervical node","Peri-umbilical nodule","Succussion splash","Palpable liver edge"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a massively dilated stomach full of fluid, with a mass in the antrum. Combined with the clinical picture of progressive upper abdominal pain, vomiting, and inability to tolerate solids, this is highly suggestive of gastric outlet obstruction due to a stenosing carcinoma of the antrum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E succussion splash\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely physical sign to be evident in this case. It is characteristic of gastric outlet obstruction, where fluid accumulates in a dilated stomach. The splash is elicited by gently rocking the patient\u0027s abdomen from side to side, producing a splashing sound as fluid moves within the distended stomach. This is usually evident to the listening, without the need of using a stethoscope.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShifting dullness\u003C/strong\u003E is a sign of ascites, where free fluid in the peritoneal cavity moves with changes in patient position. While advanced gastric cancer can cause ascites, it is not a typical early finding and is not suggested by the CT images provided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E palpable cervical node\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as Virchow\u0027s node, can be a sign of metastatic gastric cancer. However, it typically occurs in more advanced stages and is not the most likely finding in this presentation of gastric outlet obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E peri-umbilical nodule\u003C/strong\u003E, or Sister Mary Joseph\u0027s nodule, is a sign of peri-umbilical metastasis that can occur in advanced abdominal or pelvic malignancies, including gastric cancer. However, it is a rare and late finding, not typically seen in the initial presentation of gastric outlet obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epalpable liver edge\u003C/strong\u003E could indicate hepatomegaly, which might be seen in liver metastases from gastric cancer. However, liver metastases are not evident on the CT images provided, and hepatomegaly is not a characteristic finding in early gastric outlet obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the succussion splash is the most likely physical sign in this case of gastric outlet obstruction. It directly relates to the pathophysiology of the obstruction, where the stomach becomes dilated and filled with fluid due to the distal obstruction caused by the antral carcinoma. The other signs, while potentially associated with gastric cancer, are less likely to be present at this stage of the disease or in this specific presentation of gastric outlet obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gastric outlet obstruction due to antral carcinoma typically presents with upper abdominal pain, vomiting, and inability to tolerate solids.","A succussion splash is a characteristic physical sign of gastric outlet obstruction, indicating fluid retention in a dilated stomach.","CT imaging is valuable in diagnosing gastric outlet obstruction and identifying the underlying cause, such as antral carcinoma."],"references":["Coburn N, Cosby R, Klein L, et al. Staging and surgical approaches in gastric cancer: A systematic review. Cancer Treatment Rev. 2018; 63:104-15. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29275224/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38132"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14108"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20994"},{"type":"media","id":"20995"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20994"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/AEJ6nOLifZfAMuWebRcAav1pG8GVBI.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/AEJ6nOLifZfAMuWebRcAav1pG8GVBI.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":487,"height":380}},{"type":"media","id":"20995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20995"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1GXgEmifyeeyeKqysrhpEwqRlS7LM9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1GXgEmifyeeyeKqysrhpEwqRlS7LM9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":380,"height":422}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38132"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-09T14:16:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-09T14:16:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6787"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52757"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag